A worker at Tepito. Tepito is known as one of the more dangerous neighborhoods of Mexico City because it is essentially a black market for counterfeit goods and drugs. Also, the de facto patron saint of the area is Santa Muerte (Our Holy Lady of Death). The entire culture is really fascinating - especially coming from American culture where a topic like death is rarely discussed and is seen as taboo. It’s been such an interesting process exploring this area and getting to know some of the people who live here, as well as using photography to capture the humanity of a social class that is largely ignored. 
.
.
.

A man selling plants in Mexico City. It took a little convincing before he allowed me to take this portrait because I was feeling a little off that day. I also think it didn’t help that I was alone when I approached him, as I tend to be less confident in my approach when I’m alone versus when I have someone with me. People seem to have this innate animal instinct that can quickly escalate into defensiveness or fear. The trick is to learn how to override any fight or flight instinct and show that you are in no way a threat. Then it feels like riding a wave where you become cognizant of every little gesture or tone in your voice, similar to public speaking or performing. However, when I initially approached him I could feel my nerves get the best of me and could sense him pulling away. He told me I couldn’t take his photo. But I continued speaking with him in my broken Spanish with a smile and was able to finally win his trust back and I wound up taking a bunch of portraits. This is what I love about portrait photography: it’s so challenging and there’s no faking it. When someone isn’t genuinely smiling or doesn’t trust the photographer you can see it from a mile away.

An armed security guard. I love approaching people who I assume would not want their photograph taken and then get surprised by how willingly open they are. I’ve found that people with the toughest exteriors are usually the kindest. My goal is to cut through the masks most of us wear in order to connect with and capture our internal humanity.

I’ve never really photographed skateboarding before even though it’s always seemed to exist in the periphery of my life. However, when I met pro skater @oscarmeza a few months ago, I was given the opportunity to tag along and document him doing his thing. I was immediately amazed at how much tenacity and fortitude it required just to create a single video. It’s like watching a television show being filmed live, where you’re suddenly privy to the creative process of actors flubbing a line in order to get to that one perfect take. But instead, it’s a professional athlete falling hard onto concrete, getting up, and doing it all over again. Much respect ✨

It’s crazy to think a year has already passed since going on tour with @incubusofficial. I finally got around to uploading all of the portraits I took for the “yearbook” I made onto my website (link in bio). 
I shot nearly all of these over the course of an afternoon. I didn’t have a studio so I had to MacGyver it a bit: I used a beer banner that the venue had laying around that I taped to a wall as a backdrop and then used the light that was bouncing off a semi-trailer as a giant light box. I decided to take these photos for a couple of reasons: firstly, because I’m always amazed at how many people it takes to run a tour - from the managers to the instrument technicians to the video crew to the caterers to the audio engineers to the bus drivers. It’s an entire village of people that largely go unseen by the audience, but are integral for making the concerts run smoothly. Secondly, it was a way for me to get to know the crew better. I hadn’t been on a tour in awhile and I was definitely rusty. Meanwhile, I was dealing with people who have spent years on the road and I needed to break the ice a bit more. I’ve always felt more comfortable speaking with people one-on-one and especially while having a camera in my hands, so this was a way of understanding, communicating and showing my appreciation. ✨ sorry I couldn’t tag everyone..there are just too many people…but please share :) also, thanks again to @daniel who helped me at a time when things were really down 💛✨🙏

This portrait of @pat_schiller was the first cover I shot for @nytmag. @staceylbaker edited the story. I was young and very green (I think this was the third professional editorial assignment I had ever shot!). It was a very surreal moment in my life because, as a teenager, the walls of my room weren’t covered in the typical posters most teenage boys had, but were instead covered in NYTM covers and photo essays by all of the editorial heavyweights of the time. Instagram didn’t exist and it was thanks to my friends and fellow RIT alumni @yesiamoninsta and @gabrielleplucknette that I was even able to get my foot in the door and my work in front of @kathyryan This was a lifetime achievement for me and it still blows my mind to this day. It makes me feel nostalgic ✨

This is a portrait I took the other week in Texas while working alongside legendary documentary film director, James Marsh. I like this portrait because it wasn’t set up in any way. He was reviewing footage and I loved the way the light looked, so I called his name and he looked over at me and I took this picture. That’s the beauty of documentary photography: when everything comes together in a perfect, magical moment that could not have been curated any better. 
.
.
.
#jamesmarsh #bts #behindthescenes #christaanfelber #portrait #environmentalportrait #documentary #pulsefilms

Here are a few images I took for the story on @johnfetterman a few weeks ago for @menshealthmag. When I first approached him at a rally he was attending in Pittsburgh, he joked with me, asking me if I could photoshop abs onto him. He was very self-conscious - and I understand why. In a world where anyone who has a social media account can take a shot at you, it takes courage to be able to put yourself out there. I explained to him that this wasn’t simply about physical health, but about mental health as well. Politics aside, mental health is something that is obviously taking a huge toll on the people in this country - from suicides (in 2021, 54% of all gun-related deaths in the U.S. were suicides) to the staggering number of mass shootings, to people taking medications for some form of mental health issue. It’s something that also seems to go hand-in-hand with working in a creative field, so I’m sure many of you reading this have been there before. It’s obviously a very complex issue that requires nuanced discussion, but the first step is talking about these topics openly. Thank you @johnfetterman for your trust and openness and @runred @menshealthmag for the opportunity ✨💛
.
.
.
#johnfetterman #menshealthmagazine #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #editorialphotography #portraitphotography

The galley copy of my latest book, “Bittersweet.” It’s around 99.9 % complete - just a few minor changes. I’ve been working on this for the past 3 years and went through around 27,000 photos to make this edit. It’s like the journey of a diamond: exploring, mining, sorting, cutting and then polishing in order to make sure that the final product is as pure as possible. The entire process has been particularly emotional because the content is so personal. I can say for sure, though, that I’m very proud of this book and I can’t wait to finally get it out in the world. 💎
.
.
.
.
.

Friends, family, community: It’s finally here. BITTERSWEET, the book I’ve been working on for the past 3 years, is now available for pre-order! 

BITTERSWEET is easily the most vulnerable, personal work I have ever made. It has been an exhausting, yet cathartic process. And I’m so grateful and excited to get it out into the world.

This is my new book. It’s 144 color images. It took me around three years of editing. Of cutting and pruning and flipping and resizing until it felt just right. These images are a departure from my usual work in that they are not about a specific subject and most are not beautiful in the traditional or expected sense. 

I wanted to put together a body of work that felt raw and uncomfortably real. Together they are an examination of myself and a meditation on life in all of its imperfections. About finding the beauty in the full-spectrum of experiences. It was an intimidating book to assemble and it’s scary putting it out there, but here it is. 

You can preorder it at the link in my bio. The first 50 should hopefully ship out by mid December and will be signed. 

Thank you for your support 💛
